definition.value: The beta-stereoisomer of allolactose.
The alpha-stereoisomer of allolactose.
A compound in which two monosaccharides are joined by a glycosidic bond.
A dihydroxybenzoate having the two hydroxy groups located at the 3- and 4-positions.
A monoester of a dicarboxylic acid.
A glycine or taurine amide of a bile acid.
A but-2-enoic acid having a cis- double bond at C-2.
A but-2-enoate having a cis- double bond at C-2.
An organosulfonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of taurocholic acid.
The conjugate base of but-2-enoic acid.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from molybdic acid
A salt of a bile acid.
A hydroxycinnamic acid that is cinnamic acid in which the phenyl ring is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4. It exists in cis and trans forms; the latter is the more common.
A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of a proton from telluric acid.
A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of orthotelluric acid where one of the six OH groups has been deprotonated.
The glycerol phosphate ester of a phosphocholine. A nutrient with many different roles in human health.
A particle smaller than an atom.
Any molecular entity consisting of more than one atom.
An ion consisting of more than one atom.

Glycerol in which the hydrogen of one of the primary hydroxy groups is substituted by a 4-chlorophenyl group. It has antifungal and antibacterial properties, and is used for treatment of cutaneous and vaginal infections. Its 1-carbamate is used as a skeletal muscle relaxant for the treatment of painful muscle spasm.
The (Z)-isomer of 2-methylbut-2-enoic acid. It is found in plant species of the family Apiaceae.
A branched-chain fatty acid consisting of 2-butenoic acid having a methyl group at position 2.
An aromatic amino-acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N-methylanthranilic acid.
The conjugate base of 3-hydroxy-4-methylanthranilic acid.
